About
Situated west of Kensington Gardens, this city park is particularly attractive in the spring when tulips are in full bloom, and in summer when performances are staged at the open-air theater.

    Beautiful park but attracts some strange people - visitors please don't feed the fish, or birds!!!
    Visited on a very cold day in January however the scenery was lovely. Really annoying to see people coming to the park with bags full of processed pellets for the fish and chucking the whole bag into the pond. We saw two couples dump a huge amount of 'food' in the space of 10 minutes. If people care so much about the animals, why don't you read the signs or educate yourself on what not to feed them? At the park there were peacocks too which surprised me! Well only two peacocks in the dark which seemed bored and lonely... again, there were groups of people 'feeding' them and making a ruckus.
    Visited January 2024

There are better parks to visit and this is a local park for locals.
Sep 2024 • Couples
The park is a ten-minute walk from Holland Park station. It is located in a high-market area with expensive homes and the locals are wealthy. The park is distinctly average in all manners with its features being small. The park is quite busy and seating can be difficult to acquire. It is quiet in parts but does get busy. There is a function building that holds events. It is a place to people watch more than anything, but it is not worth going out of your way to visit. It is famous for its Koyto garden, which is also an average experience. There are better parks to visit and this is a local park for locals.
Written September 30, 2024

London, UK1,296 contributions
Worth a visit!
Jul 2024 • Friends
Such a lovely park with many interesting features. The Kyoto Garden is peaceful and a wonderful place to sit, has a waterfall too. The park is 55 acres so you could spend the best part of a day walking around. There is a restaurant and a cafe selling drinks and gelato. Other features include the Dutch gardens, an adventure playground, tennis courts, the Ice House and sculptures dotted around. It really is worth a visit. The Design Museum is just outside the park so that could be included too.
